Defendant Chester Anderson Smith in court with attorney Richard Jeffrey Carpenter.  Defendant Chester Anderson Smith in custody.  
James C. Griffin appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Deputy Court Clerk: dds.  


Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by the state, defense, and defendant. 

The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 42 MONTHS, CONSECUTIVE to any other sentence with credit for 92 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 24 MONTHS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 18 MONTHS.

The defendant IS NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.  The defendant IS eligible for the Substance Abuse Program AFTER SERVING 12 MONTHS OF INITIAL CONFINEMENT.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
*AODA assessment and complete follow-up care/treatment;
*Absolute sobriety- no illegal drugs unless prescribed by physician;
*Cooperate with random urine screens- no positive results;
*No contact with known drug users or locations where illegal substances are trafficked or consumed;
*No contact with Jeremy S.;
*Participate in Cognitive behavior therapy program and any other programming deemed appropriate by the department/agent;
*Seek/maintain full time employment;
*If not previously done, provide DNA sample- pay surcharge;
*Pay all applicable mandatory surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs by the end of supervision period- any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment;

State in compliance with victim rights legislation.  The Court orders restitution in the stipulated amount of $1986.00 to Jeremy S.  The Court ordered defendant to pay a fine of $2400.00 plus all mandatory costs, penalties, surcharges, including $50.00 ignition interlock surcharge. Court ordered AODA assessment and Driver's Safety Plan.  Court ordered defendant's driving privileges revoked for a period of 2 years.  Court ordered defendant restricted to operation of vehicles equipped with an ignition interlock device for 1 year.  The Court ordered that all financial obligations and restitution be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.  Appeal rights given.
